    <item>
      <title>Is It Possible To Earn Quick Money Online?</title>
      <link>http://www.businessideascenter.com/small-business-idea/earn-quick-money-online/</link>
      <comments>http://www.businessideascenter.com/small-business-idea/earn-quick-money-online/#comments</comments>
      <pubDate>Tue, 21 Jul 2009 14:07:33 +0000</pubDate>
      <dc:creator>Business Ideas Center</dc:creator>
      <category><![CDATA[Small Business Idea]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[earn quick money]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.businessideascenter.com/?p=55</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[With the recession and the job market the way it is my sister-in-law is looking for a way to earn quick money.  Can she do it online and can she do it quickly?  Well, yes and no.  She absolutely can earn money online but it will take a little bit of time.
Here&#8217;s why.
When you create [...]]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>With the recession and the job market the way it is my sister-in-law is looking for a way to earn quick money.  Can she do it online and can she do it quickly?  Well, yes and no.  She absolutely can earn money online but it will take a little bit of time.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s why.</p>
<p>When you create a new site with a new domain, the search engines need to index your site.  What that means is that the search engines (Google, Yahoo, Bing etc.) have to crawl your site, see what you have for content on your site and then add it to their files.  That&#8217;s the layman&#8217;s explanation for it!  This can take days to weeks.  Having your site on a blog and writing posts to it every day using your main keyword phrases helps it get indexed much quicker than a regular site.  That&#8217;s why I always recommend using a blog like one from wordpress.org.</p>
<p>Okay, after the site gets indexed the search engines then go and look to see if anyone is linking to your site.  They think that if other similar sites that they like are linking to your site you must be pretty good and they will begin to rank you a little higher on their search engine.  It takes a little bit of time to build these links because you have to do it manually in order to get &#8220;organic&#8221; backlinks.</p>
<p>Then you can also start submitting your posts and content to social bookmarking sites that also help you build links and you can then begin to build relationships with other sites.  ll of this takes some time and your marketing efforts will be a daily event and not something you do once or twice and think it&#8217;s done.</p>
<p>Every good online marketer knows you can make some serious cash online but you need to put in the effort and it will take some time.  Plan on a few months to start seeing some decent traffic if you put a marketing plan in place and stick to it.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
      <wfw:commentRss>http://www.businessideascenter.com/small-business-idea/earn-quick-money-online/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
      <slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>10 Tips to Balance Your Home Based Small Business</title>
      <link>http://www.businessideascenter.com/home-based-small-business/10-tips-balance-home-based-small-business/</link>
      <comments>http://www.businessideascenter.com/home-based-small-business/10-tips-balance-home-based-small-business/#comments</comments>
      <pubDate>Mon, 20 Jul 2009 14:10:04 +0000</pubDate>
      <dc:creator>Business Ideas Center</dc:creator>
      <category><![CDATA[Home Based Small Business]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.businessideascenter.com/?p=56</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[I am a stay at home mom.  I juggle my family&#8217;s daily routines, food shopping, cleaning, laundry, cooking, and of course my own online business.  I have a laptop that I drag from room to room to room and I camp out wherever I can find an empty seat.  I work a [...]]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img class="alignleft" style="border: 0pt none; margin: 6px;" src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2425/3715946984_0dbe62157c_m.jpg" border="0" alt="Balancing Your Home Based Business " width="240" height="180" />I am a stay at home mom.  I juggle my family&#8217;s daily routines, food shopping, cleaning, laundry, cooking, and of course my own online business.  I have a laptop that I drag from room to room to room and I camp out wherever I can find an empty seat.  I work a lot of hours during the week and that&#8217;s just on my business.</p>
<p>You may be wondering how I get all that done.  I sometimes wonder too!  I have trained myself to work around my family, when my kids are at school, and I often work late at night.  I also work weekends.  But I am home with my kids, I have attended every single event at my daughter&#8217;s school, I have gone on field trips with her class, I bring her to gymnastics on Tuesday afternoons and I&#8217;m a Girl Scout Cookie Mom Friday afternoons.  I couldn&#8217;t possibly do all that if I worked outside my home, which I did for 18 years until I had my 2nd daughter in 2001.  I&#8217;ve been working from home ever since and I wouldn&#8217;t trade it for the world.</p>
<p>So how do you balance a home based small business with your own life and family?</p>
<p>Here are 10 tips to help you:</p>
<ol>
<li>Get organized.  Make folders for your important papers and how-to information so you can refer back to them as you need to.  There is a lot to know when you are building your business and if you start from the very beginning by being organized you&#8217;ll save yourself some valuable time.  And since you work for yourself time is money.</li>
<li>Create a very basic business plan.  I&#8217;m not one for long drawn out plans but I do believe in having a very good idea of what you want to accomplish with your business so you don&#8217;t get sidetracked with other less important avenues.  State your mission or goals for your company and what you plan to do with your business.  Decide the who, what, where, when and why of your business and put it in writing so you can refer to it often.</li>
<li>Create Lists. Write these down or use Excel to create lists of tasks you need to get done.  You can download templates from Excel that help you create these lists.</li>
<li>Use a scale to prioritize your tasks.  On a scale of 1-10 or 1-50 (It really depends on how many tasks you have) rate them in the order in which they are the most imperative to get done.  Then start working on them in that order.</li>
<li>Set small goals that you can achieve and progress from there.  Once you know your tasks, break them down into small goals that you can achieve in chunks.  This will help make the task a little less daunting!</li>
<li>Set a schedule to help you stick to your work.  I know that I can work from 9a-3pm M-F during the school year without interruption because my kids are at school.  I also know that I can work early on Sat/Sun because I am a morning person and everyone else in my family will be sleeping until 10am!  So I know that I can fit in the hours I need to even though it is broken up throughout the day.  I stop working at 3pm and spend the rest of the afternoon with my kids.  After they go to bed I occasionally pop back online to check my mail and to update my Twitter, Facebook and other accounts.  Find out what works for you and try to set a schedule for yourself.</li>
<li>Set up down time as well to decompress at the end of the day.  Stop working at least an hour before going to bed or you will never wind down long enough to fall asleep.  Trust me on this one.  Entrepreneurs&#8217; minds never stop.  Get a tape recorder and leave it near your bed if you can&#8217;t shut your mind off at night.</li>
<li>Focus on what you want, not what you don&#8217;t want.  This is pretty cool actually.  When you focus on what it is you are trying to achieve and NOT on what you won&#8217;t want to have happen you will actually be sending out brain waves with a frequency to them that attract like brainwaves.  Okay, so what the heck does that mean?  It means &#8220;like attracts like&#8221;.  Start focusing on what it is that you DO want. For example, &#8220;I want to work from home so I can be with my family and be successful in my career&#8221;.  Versus, &#8220;I don&#8217;t want to have to go back to that awful job where my boss yells at me all day&#8221;.  See the difference?</li>
<li>Outsource.  There are plenty of outsourcing solutions available at pretty affordable prices.  Odesk is one of them and Guru.com is another great one for virtual assistants.  Or consider hiring a college student to do some content writing for you.  College kids are brilliant with computers and can work for great wages.  You may even be able to find some students that would write for you as part of their college course.  Check around with colleges to see what they recommend.</li>
<li>Get support from your family.  You may be surprised at how willing they are to help you when you tell them that they can&#8217;t have any fresh baked chocolate chips cookies after school if you can&#8217;t finish your work on time or that your husband may have to stop at the grocery store on his way home if you can&#8217;t get that last task checked off.  You may be surprised!</li>
</ol>
<p>Nadine McNeil<br />
Founder of The <a href="http://businessideascenter.com">Business Ideas Center</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
      <wfw:commentRss>http://www.businessideascenter.com/home-based-small-business/10-tips-balance-home-based-small-business/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
      <slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
    </item>
